   tins ahead of time for Toby and Anton to have for breakfast. They‚Äôre
   delicious for afternoon snacks, too.

   I am ‚Äúwhy do I need Venmo?‚Äù years old. Made me laugh.

   What a beautiful candle.

   Found! The fastest way to board an airplane.

   How to make work trips a little easier. ‚ÄúSend selfie videos. Because
   your kids ‚Äì and your spouse ‚Äì miss you. And a five-second video of you
   standing on the airport‚Äôs moving walkway while making silly faces will
   delight them infinitely more than a photo or phone call will.‚Äù

   America‚Äôs 10 best new restaurants. (The photos look so delicious.)

   Also, what do you like to wear to work? We‚Äôre writing a post about what
   our readers wear to work and we‚Äôd love to hear from you. If you‚Äôd like,
   please send your look to kim@cupofjo.com. Please include a photo, where
   you live and a couple sentences about your work style. xoxo

   Plus, two reader comments:

   Says Alice on 12 questions to ask your significant other at dinner: we
   recently instated a date rule that if we want to talk about work, we
   have to touch our nose the whole time. Just goofy and annoying enough
   to encourage us talk about the truly important things, like:
   ‚Äì if you had to eat the same meal once a day every day, what would it
   be?
   ‚Äì what movie could you happily watch once a week for the rest of your
   life?
   and, if you‚Äôre feeling brave, the nearly marriage-ending
   ‚Äì what is closer to a fry, a sweet potato fry or a tater tot?‚Äù

   Says Emma on burning questions about food: ‚ÄúTo take care of food waste,
   we have ‚ÄòTiny Bites‚Äô once a week. The idea is a plate full of any
   leftovers. Favorites include: halved meatballs, three carrot sticks, a
   dollop of hummus, apple slices, a pile of peas, cubed cheese, raisins
   no one ate from their lunch, yogurt with leftover herbs, bits of chips
